Body Iron storage

+ **2/3 ferritin** - water soluble, small amount found in plasma, *acute phase protein -> rises with infection / inflamation*
+ **1/3 haemosiderin** - found within macrophages of the RET, visible under LM when stained with Perl's stain.

[!INFO] Brief note about the role of the spleen in RBC destruction
The spleen is a mass of lymphoid tissue.
The capsule has invaginations called septa which carry branches of the splenic artery into this lymphoid tissue.
The spleen as white pulp - lymphoid nodules and red pulp - sinusoids.
Some branches of the splenic arteries ('penicillar arteries') end blindly and dump blood into the splenic stroma. Functioning RBCs then migrate into sinusoids which act as sieves and then renter the cirulation. Old non functional RBCs cannot enter the sinusoids and get destroyed in the spleen. Removal of RBCs and recyling their iron is a main role of the red pulp.

Causes of elevated ferritin

Elevated ferritin usually indicates iron overload;
Other causes of increased ferritin are:

  1. ? acute phase reactions
  2. Acute illnesses with haemophagocytosis -
    • Hemophagocytosis : phagocytosis of erythrocytes, lymphocytes or other hematopoietic precursors by histiocytes or macrophages either in bone marrow, lymph node, liver or spleen.
    • Rapid, massive increases in ferritin. (much higher than in iron overload illnesses)
    • HLH
    • HIV infection - independent of iron status, specially with low CD4 counts and with opprotunistic infection.
  3. Chronic inflammatory conditions
    1. metabolic syndrome
    2. DM
    3. Still's disease
    4. In most inflammatory states the degree of ferritin elevation does not exceed two to three times normal (is higher in iron overload), the transferrin saturation (TSAT) typically does not exceed 45 percent, and there are other features of the clinical picture or signs of inflammation such as increased C-reactive protein (CRP) and other acute phase reactants
  4. Liver disease - liver damage -> acute phase response -> increased ferritin.
    1. Also, liver damage -> release of stored iron -> increased ferritin
  5. Malignancy

Haemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis

Immune hyperactivation causing tissue damage; life threatening.
Acutely ill patient. Occurs in children and adults.
fever, hepatosplenomegaly, rash, neurologic findings, and pancytopenia can occur.
Macrophage activation syndrome is similar.

Still's disease

Source
Adult-onset Stills disease is the adult form of systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis
Quotidian fever, arthritis, lymphadenopathy, sore throat and evanescent (lasting less than 24 hours) rash.
Rash mostly affects chest and thighs.
AOSD is a diagnosis of exclusion;

Patterns of Still's disease:
monophasic: single episode which lasts weeks to months;
Polyphasic: patients are asymptomatic for weeks to years between episodes; severity decreases over time.
chronic: chronic disease; articular symptoms predominate.

G6PD deficiency

DOC in pregnancy is LMWH = Enoxaparin
Edoxaban and dabigatran - preceded by parenteral therapy for 5 days followed by a switch to [[General Medicine 4#DOACs|DOACs]]. i.e : no overlap , unlike with warfarin.
Anticoagulants prevent clot extension but do no dissolve formed clots.

  1. More than one episode of unprovoked proximal DVT or symptomatic PE -> indefinite anticoagulation
  2. For most patients with a first episode of unprovoked proximal DVT and/or symptomatic PE -> indefinite anticoagulation.
  3. Patients with active cancer -> may need indefinite anticoagulation (compare with risk of bleeding)

Pulmonary emoblism

#2022SBR Q16


Obstruction of the pulmonary artery of one of it's branches with thrombus, tumour, air, fat etc.

We'll focus on thromboembolism induced PE.

Pathogenesis of pulmonary embolism

Most PE arises from proximal DVT of the lower limbs.
Risk factors are the same.
Pulmonary emboli are usually multiple, most affecting the lower lobes.

Pulmonary emboli have the following effects of haemodynamics and gas exchange:

  • Two mechanisms cause hypoxia and respiratory alkalosis;
    • about 10% have small emboli that lodge distally causing infarction -> inflammation -> pleuritic chest pain + haemoptysis
    • Local inflammation -> surfactant dysfunction -> atelectasis -> intrapulmonary shunting
    • Obstruction of vessels -> decreased local perfusion of lung tissue
    • hypoxia and inflammation -> increased respiratory drive -> hypocapnea and respiratory alkalosis.
  • Haemodynamics - increased pulmonary circulation resistance -> increases RV afterload -> RV strain -> RV failure + RV dilation -> decreased LV filling. (IVS bowing and decreased RV output) -> hypotension
    • Normally, multiple large thrombi are required to significantly increase pulmonary pressure and cause RV failure, unless the patient has preexisting cardio / pulmonary disease.
    • Fluid administration during resuscitation (must be limited) and intubation (ideally avoid) can further compromise RV function.
    • PE can be classified based on haemodynamic effect: [[#Classification of PE]]

Classification of PE

Pulmonary embolism can be classified based on several criteria:

  • Haemodynamic effect -
    • Haemodyanically unstable PE = hypotension present; (aka. massive)
    • Haemodynamically stable
      • submassive / intermediate risk - RV strain.
      • low risk - no RV strain
  • Progression of symptoms
    • Acute - immediate onset of symptoms
    • Subacute - patient presents within days or weeks
    • Chronic - Patient slowly develops pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH)
  • Anatomic location
    • 3-6% saddle
    • Small thrombi in the peripheral segmental / subsegmental branches are more likely to cause pulmonary infarction. Inflammation -> pleuritic pain.
  • Symptomatic / asymptomatic
    • Asymptomatic means incidental finding on radiography.

Presentation of PE

The most common presenting symptom is dyspnea followed by chest pain (classically pleuritic in nature, but not always), cough, and symptoms of deep venous thrombosis. Hemoptysis is an unusual presenting symptom. With severe PE, patients can present with shock, arrhythmia, or syncope. Many patients are asymptomatic; high index of suspicion is needed.

Treatment

Mainstay is anticoagulation.
Thrombolysis / embolectomy / IVC filter is reserved for PE with life threatening hypotension.

Haemodynamically unstable -> thrombolysis (if thrombolysis is contraindicated, embolectomy)
Haemodynamically stable and low risk -> anticoagulation.
Haemodynamically stable and intermediate risk -> angicoagulation

Selection of anticoagulant agent

[!TIP] mnemonic for best anticoagulant in special situations
Liver failure -> LMWH
Kidney failure -> VKA
Pregnancy = Mother -> LMWH

Long term outcomes

Commonest early complication is recurrence; risk is reduced by anticoagulation.
Commonest late complication is CTEPH.
Bleeding from anticoagulation.

Casts

Represents protein precipitated in the distal convoluted tubules.
Composed of Tamm-Horsfall protein which is made by the renal tubular epithelium.

  • Hyaline casts - only tamm horsfall protein; least significant type of cast.
  • Granular casts - consist of cell debris, plasma proteins (fibrinogen, immune complexes). Seen in
    • Course, deeply pigmented, muddy brown casts are considered characteristic of ATN. a
    • Pyelonephritis
    • Glomerulonephritis
    • Malignant nephrosclerosis
    • Presence of red cells in the case => Glomerular injury.
  • Fatty casts / urinary lipids (cholesterol esters) : nephrotic syndrome, mercury poisoning, ethylene glycol poisoning.
  • RBC casts - Hallmark of glomerulonephritis; esp. proliferative glomerulonephritis.
  • WBC casts - interstitial nephritis, pyelonephritis.
  • Tubular epithelial cell casts : ATN, acute interstitial nephritis, proliferative glomerulonephritis.

Cells in the urine

Normal looking RBCs can be seen in any cause of macroscopic or microscopic haematuria.
Dysmorphic RBCs are suggestive of glomerular disease. (esp. acanthocytse - specificity of 98% for glomerulonephritis). RBC casts also suggest glomerulonephritis.

WBCs - usually associated with bacterial infection; also nephrolithiasis / interstitial nephritis.
